LUMPY SKIN DISEASE, BOVINE - CYPRUS (04): (NORTHERN CYPRUS), CONTROL POLICY DISCUSSED
*************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Fri 12 Dec 2014
Source: Philenews.com (Republic of Cyprus) [in Greek, machine trans. summarized, edited]
http://www.philenews.com/el-gr/koinonia-eidiseis/160/232681/se-terastio-kindyno-i-ageladotrofia-apo-tin-lsd-sta-katechomena


There is serious risk that lumpy skin disease (LSD) in cattle is spreading from the affected location in Northern Cyprus. The European Community authorities are taking very strict measures regarding this disease, which has never entered the EU.

EU experts who arrived here last weekend visited the infected farms in [Northern Cyprus] on Wednesday [10 Dec 2014]. Yesterday [Thu 11 Dec 2014], they held a meeting with the Veterinary Services [Nicosia, Republic of Cyprus] and reported about their observations. It became apparent that if the disease enters the territory controlled by the Republic of Cyprus, severe control measures, such as the killing of positive animals and vaccinations, will be required, and Cyprus will enter a 3-year period of export prohibitions of meat and cow's milk.

It was also said that in such a scenario, EU's Standing Committee on the Food Chain and Animal Health in Brussels is likely to impose restrictions upon the exports of Halloumi from Cyprus to the member states, unless it is made from 100 percent goat's milk. [Halloumi is a Cypriot semi-hard, unripened brined cheese, traditionally made from a mixture of goat's and sheep's milk but in recent years sometimes also including cow's milk. Halloumi is Cyprus's 2nd biggest export to overseas markets. In 2013, exports were worth Euro 76.4 million [USD 102 million], up 26 percent on the prior year. - Mod.AS].

Although all indications show that the disease was transferred to [Northern Cyprus] from Turkey, so far this has not been confirmed, the mode of transmission remaining unknown. Experts say it might have originated either from contaminated imported hay or was airborne by mosquitoes.

At yesterday's [11 Dec 2014] meeting with the visiting experts, it was reported that LSD cases have been identified on 8 different holdings, all in the Karpas peninsula [see comment]. The experts suggested that vaccination should be applied.

[On 12 Dec 2012], cattle breeders were invited to the Veterinary Services where the need for spraying insecticides [or repellents? - Mod.AS] in local cattle plants was explained. The Health services, on their side, take care of spraying along the Green Line [the line dividing the Island of Cyprus between the Greek and Turkish entities - Mod.AS].

[Byline: Angel Nicholas]

