******
[2]
Date: Sat 13 Dec 2014
Source: Near East University (Northern Turkey) website [summarized, edited]
http://duyuru.neu.edu.tr/?p=83579


According to the press release from the Directorate of Press and Public Relations Office of the Near East University, Prof. Dr. Omer Memduh Esendal, Dean of NEU Faculty of Veterinary Medicine, stated that LSD virus had affected the animals in TRNC [Northern Cyprus; the self-declared "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus"], recently adding that there was no scientific evidence that LSD virus affects humans.

"Lumpy skin disease, known as exanthema nodularis bovis, is a contagious viral disease of cattle that is characterized by rough skin nodules in hazelnut or walnut size. LSD is a notifiable disease. In case of LSD suspicion, state authorities should be notified immediately. Animals suspected with LSD should be isolated, and the farm should be quarantined until definitive diagnosis is determined," noted Esendal.

Stating that lumpy skin disease was caused by a virus in the family Poxviridae, genus Capripoxvirus, Professor Esendal noted: "This genus is closely related antigenically to sheep and goat pox viruses. LSD is usually seen in cattle in a wide range of ecotypes in Africa, where, in the last 20 years, it appears to have spread to virtually all countries on the continent.

Highlighting that the morbidity rate in cattle is 40 percent and mortality is low in most cases, varying from 1 to 10 percent, Professor Esendal said: "The disease may rarely cause abortion in pregnant [animals]. Dependent on the stage of the disease, reduction in milk production, fatigue, emaciation, loss of fertility and lameness can be seen."

"LSD is a contagious disease transmitted from animal to animal primarily by biting insects, particularly mosquitoes. As virus can be present in cutaneous lesions, saliva, nasal discharge, milk, and semen, direct contact is also a source of infections. There is no scientific evidence that LSD virus can be transmitted from animals to humans," said Esendal.

Touching upon the importance of taking measures for combating the disease, Professor Esendal noted: "As lumpy skin disease spreads by biting flies and mosquitoes, which feed on the skin lesions, it is very important to fight against the biting insect vectors to prevent LSD. To this end, all known preventive measures including strict biosecurity and hygiene applications on livestock premises should be taken necessarily in a timely manner. Good biosecurity is a vital part of keeping disease away from animals. It also helps to improve farm efficiency, protect neighboring farms and the countryside. If lumpy skin disease is confirmed, animals suspected with LSD should be isolated, and the farm should be quarantined. Cleaning and disinfection of premises, insect control, depopulation of the infected animals and proper disposal of carcasses are of utmost importance."

When high fever, nodules on the skin, emaciation, enlarged lymph nodes, edema of the skin are seen, LSD can be suspected. However, definitive diagnosis is possible by detection of the virus by proper tests in laboratory conditions. Before collecting or sending any samples for diagnostic test, the respective authorities should be contacted. Material for virus isolation and antigen detection should be collected by biopsy or at post-mortem from skin nodules, lung lesions or lymph nodes. Samples for virus isolation and antigen-detection should be collected within the 1st week of the occurrence of clinical signs. Samples should only be sent under secure conditions and to authorized laboratories to prevent the spread of the disease.

There is no specific treatment for the disease.

Animals infected with LSD virus generally recover in time. Complete recovery may take several months. Within this process, antibiotics can be administrated to prevent or control secondary infections.

Indicating that vaccination against LSD has been successfully practiced in many countries in Africa, Professor Esendal noted: "There is no specific vaccination program against LSD in TRNC or Turkey [re. Turkey, see comment]. However, as LSD virus belongs to the same family as sheep and goat pox virus, sheep and goat pox vaccines can be used for the prevention of LSD."

