Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The Karpas Peninsula, where all described LSD cases in Cyprus are located, a long, finger-like peninsula in northeast Cyprus, is one of the most prominent geographical features of the island. It is about 70 km from continental Turkey. Its farthest extent, Cape Apostolos Andreas, is about 100 km from the Syrian coast to the east.

Turkey, reportedly infected by LSD virus since summer 2013, applies "Vaccination in response to the outbreak." On 22 Jul 2014, Turkey submitted its final OIE report, stating: "The event is unlikely to be contained and is now considered to be endemic. No more follow-up reports will be made, but instead, information about this disease will be included in the future 6-monthly reports." For the report, with vaccination figures per province (totaling more than 730 000 cattle) and an interactive map (with recent outbreaks in Turkey; the map can be centered on Cyprus and zoomed in), see http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapEventSummary&reportid=15669.

The situation in Syria is assumed to be considerably worse, but no information is officially available.

In case the disease is still limited to the Karpas Peninsula, earliest eradication deserves to be considered. "Killing of positive animals and vaccinations" may not be sufficient for this end and for the prevention of LSD spread southwards into the Republic of Cyprus (meaning LSD within the EU).

When LSD entered Israel for the 1st time in September 1989, the outbreak was controlled by stamping out. The entire cattle population in the affected village was culled, combined with vaccination of all cattle around the Gaza strip and around the infected village. It was decided to refrain from introducing an exotic vaccine strain, preferring a sheep pox vaccine strain which had been certified and applied for decades for the protection of sheep against sheep pox in Israel. The vaccine was tested for its safety and efficacy in cattle according to OIE's guidelines as outlined in the Terrestrial Manual; the trials, involving 6 susceptible 5-month old Friesian calves (4 vaccinated, challenged 21 days post vaccination and 2 controls) were performed in a containment facility at the Kimron Veterinary Institute, Beit-Dagan (Ref 1). Israel remained thereafter free from LSD for 17 years, in spite of the disease being endemic in Egypt and of infected animals discovered in the adjacent Gaza strip in 1992. Vaccinations were discontinued since 1993.

In 2006, the disease returned to Israel. Modified stamping out (killing of clinical cases) was applied. The disease continued in 2007. Since July 2012, the disease spread throughout large parts of Israel, requiring mass vaccinations, and may currently be regarded as endemic.

ProMED-mail's posting "Lumpy skin disease, bovine - Cyprus: (Northern Cyprus) RFI" (archived 20141205.3012426) included the following commentary on a field-comparative vaccination trial against LSD, performed during 2013 in Israel, addressing 2 vaccines:

1. Live attenuated RM 65 sheep pox strain (fortified) "POX-10;"
2. Live attenuated LSD vaccine "Neethling" strain.

The following text was included: "As apparent from the results, presented during Israel's 26th annual dairy science conference (Ashkelon, 29-30 Oct 2014), the Neethling vaccine conferred better protection from day 15 post-vaccination and onwards. Additional details are expected to be included in the paper when published."

In response, we received from a subscriber who preferred to remain unnamed, a response with reservations, including the following remarks: "There were many reported adverse reactions and mild disease outbreaks following the Neethling vaccine injections while hardly if any reactions following the "POX-10" usage."

Though "additional details" are expected to be included in the paper covering the said field comparative vaccination trial against LSD when published (in a scientific journal), we have asked the authors of the cited preliminary report to briefly address, at this time, the raised issue of post-vaccination reactions. The following complementary information has been kindly provided by the chief veterinarian of "Hachaklait:"

"Both "Pox-10" and "Neethling" strain vaccines had passed a limited field trial to assess the clinical safety of the 2 commercial vaccines in Israeli dairy cattle. Local reactions and systemic deviations from normal body temperature, milk production and impact upon pregnancy (abortion) were addressed. No serious or life threatening adverse events were observed in the course of this part of the trial. Based on the data generated from this study, there are no indications to doubt the clinical safety of both tested vaccines to be administered in 4-6 month-old female dairy calves as well as in adult dairy cattle during the last trimester of their pregnancy.

In the 2013 LSD outbreak, almost half of the cattle at risk had already been vaccinated with a single sheep pox strain vaccine when they were revaccinated with the Neethling strain (the reason for this revaccination was the observed deficient protection rendered by the initial vaccination with a single sheep pox RM65 dose).

Out of about 250 000 vaccinated animals, no case of death has been reported, and very small numbers (data analysis in process) of animals had shown on day 10-11 minor skin lesions, mostly without milk drop (this, in accordance with the Neethling vaccine's producer's information on 'Effects of the Vaccine')."

In reference to the comparative vaccination trial undertaken in 2013 on 15 dairy cattle operations (ProMED-mail 20141205.3012426), kindly note that all participating animals had been vaccinated with a single dose sheep-pox strain RM65 vaccine prior to the start of the trial. The number of animals with significant LSD signs was lower in the Neethling group from day-post-vaccination (DPV) 15 and onwards.

The complete data and their analysis are in process for publication in a scientific journal."

We are grateful to Dr Benny Sharir, Chief Veterinarian, "Hachaklait" and to his colleagues engaged in the trials, for kindly providing the above timely clarifications. The publication of the complete paper is anticipated with interest.

Since the issue of LSD vaccinations is increasingly becoming acute, currently in Cyprus but, unfortunately, possibly soon in additional Asian and European countries, with naive cattle threatened by LSD, controlled vaccination trials in susceptible animals seem urgently needed in order to select the safest and most efficacious vaccines.

Reference
Brenner, J.; David, D.; Avraham, A.; Klopfer-Orgad, U.; Samina, I.; Peleg, B. A. Experimental infection with local lumpy skin disease virus in cattle vaccinated with sheep pox vaccine. Israel Journal of Veterinary Medicine 47 (1), 1992, 17-21. - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3034775,82.]
